## Lambda Things

_(Run this one from the root)_

Once changes are made, build the JS:

```bash
yarn compile-lambda
```

_(Run all the following from the `/lambda` directory)_

Then build the container:

```bash
docker build -t shrekify .
```

To test, you can run it:

```bash
docker run -p 9000:8080 shrekify
```

And then invoke the function:

```bash
curl -X POST "http://localhost:9000/2015-03-31/functions/function/invocations" -H "Content-Type: application/json" -d '{"body": {"file":"", "landscape":""}}'
```

> If you're getting an error about parsing JSON, remove the parsing in the lambda function.

Since the output is in base64, you can copy it an convert it to an image using [this converter](https://codebeautify.org/base64-to-image-converter).

Once it is ready, tag and push the container (derived from [these AWS docs](https://docs.aws.amazon.com/lambda/latest/dg/images-create.html#images-upload)):

```bash
docker tag shrekify:latest <AWS-ACCOUNT-ID>.dkr.ecr.us-east-2.amazonaws.com/shrekify:latest
docker push <AWS-ACCOUNT-ID>.dkr.ecr.us-east-2.amazonaws.com/shrekify:latest
```

If not authenticated:

```bash
aws ecr get-login-password --region us-east-2 | docker login --username AWS --password-stdin <AWS-ACCOUNT-ID>.dkr.ecr.us-east-2.amazonaws.com
```

After, make sure to update the actual function to use the new image. You can do this in the UI or use:

```bash
aws lambda update-function-code --function-name shrekify --image-uri <AWS-ACCOUNT-ID>.dkr.ecr.us-east-2.amazonaws.com/shrekify:latest
```
